.TH JTUTIL-SDRAM "1" "April 2026" "jtutil-sdram manual" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
jtutil-sdram \- Convert .rom files for SDRAM simulation
.SH DESCRIPTION
Convert .rom files to sdram files for quick simulation
.PP
After you create the .rom files using jtframe mra, you can generate
the sdram*.bin simulation files without having to run a download simulation by
calling jtutil sdram.
.PP
\fBjtutil sdram\fR
must be called from within a simulation folder, such as
\fBver/game\fR.
If the simulation folder is the ROM set name, that will be used. If the folder
is just "game", then the set name must be provided in the command line.
.PP
\fBjtutil sdram\fR
will split the .rom file in the right number of sdram*bin files by
inspecting the definitions of JTFRAME_BA?_START, JTFRAME_PROM_START and
JTFRAME_HEADER.
.PP
\fBjtutil sdram\fR
will also link a rom.bin file to the .rom file used. If rom.bin
already existed, it will be deleted and re\-created as a link.
.PP
If the core uses the header for SDRAM bank assignment, special care
must be taken for the PROM data as JTFRAME_PROM_START will not be defined. This
utility will create a file for each ROM region after bank 3, so the core can
directly load these files in simulation. You can also force the PROM load in
simulation for these cores by setting the SIM_LOAD_PROM macro.
.PP
The result will only be correct for cores that do not transform download data
on the fly.
.PP
When a core defines
\fBsdram.banks[].buses[].gfx_sort\fR
in
\fBmem.yaml\fR,
\fBjtutil sdram\fR
applies the same byte\-address reordering used by the JTFRAME download path.
Per-bus
\fBoffset\fR
and
\fBaddr_width\fR
are honored, including offsets that come from
\fBparams\fR
expressions with macro references.
If a bus defines
\fBgfx_sort_en\fR,
\fBjtutil sdram\fR
applies it automatically when the enable signal name matches the game name.
The game name is derived from the current folder or from the explicit command
argument.
.PP
If
\fB--sim\fR
is used,
\fBjtutil sdram\fR
also patches the generated SDRAM bank files with the
\fBsimfile\fR
entries defined in
\fBsdram.banks[].buses[]\fR
and
\fBsdram.cache-lanes[]\fR.
Files are copied in place at the bank-relative offset defined in
\fBmem.yaml\fR,
with optional 16-bit or 32-bit byte swapping when
\fBsimfile.big_endian\fR
is true.
Optional
\fBsimfile.data_type\fR
may be
\fBu16\fR
or
\fBu32\fR;
if omitted,
\fBjtutil\fR
derives it from
\fBdata_width\fR
for 16-bit and 32-bit entries, and wider big-endian entries must set it
explicitly.
.SS "Usage:"
.IP
jtutil sdram [game\-name] [flags]
.SS "Flags:"
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
help for sdram
.TP
\fB\-\-sim\fR
Apply mem.yaml simfile overlays to SDRAM bank files
.SS "Global Flags:"
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR
Verbose
